BMP2 Signaling in Stromal Cells: Translational Evidence Across Species

Overview of Analysis

This analysis examines BMP2 expression in stromal cells across different species and its dysregulation in inflammatory conditions. The analysis focuses on two main datasets: (1) spatial transcriptomic data from juvenile rhesus macaques with antibiotic-induced dysbiosis, and (2) public single-cell RNA-seq data from human ulcerative colitis patients. The goal was to investigate whether BMP2 signaling in stromal cells represents an evolutionarily conserved mechanism in intestinal homeostasis and inflammation.

Macaque Spatial Transcriptomics Analysis

Methodology

Colon tissue samples were collected from a juvenile rhesus macaque (~1 year old) with idiopathic chronic diarrhea (ICD) and an age-matched control that was euthanized due to non-gastrointestinal issues. Spatial transcriptomic analysis was performed using the CosMx platform with the 1K Universal Panel. This panel does not include WNT4, so cells identified as WNT-secreting in this macaque dataset may be "P1-like" rather than true P1 cells. Stromal cells were identified using a multi-marker approach with positive selection for VIM, PDGFRA, and NCAM1, while excluding cells expressing PTPRC (CD45), PECAM1, and EPCAM (VIM+, PDGFRA/NCAM1+, PTPRC-/PECAM1-/EPCAM-).

Key Findings

The analysis revealed a significantly higher proportion of BMP2-expressing stromal cells in the ICD sample compared to control (21.90% vs. 10.48%, Wilcoxon rank-sum test, p = 8.02e-06). Additionally, the mean normalized expression of BMP2 was elevated in the ICD sample (0.179 vs. 0.113). Full quantitative results are presented in Table 1.

This significant enrichment of BMP2-expressing stromal cells in the macaque model of antibiotic-induced dysbiosis suggests that early-life antibiotic exposure may lead to increased BMP2 expression in stromal cells, with effects that persist into later developmental stages.

Human IBD Single-Cell RNA-seq Analysis

Methodology

The analysis utilized the Kinchen et al. (2018) dataset, which profiled colonic mesenchymal cells from 5 healthy controls and 5 ulcerative colitis patients (ages 18-90). Stromal cell subtypes were identified using established marker genes to classify five distinct populations: general stromal cells, inflammatory stromal cells, myofibroblasts, WNT-secreting stromal cells, and mesothelial cells.

BMP2 Expression Patterns

Gene expression analysis revealed differential expression of BMP2 across stromal subtypes, with particularly elevated levels in inflammatory stromal cells from UC patients (Figure 2). Quantitative analysis showed a significant increase in the percentage of BMP2-positive cells in UC compared to healthy controls (p < 0.001), with the most pronounced differences observed in inflammatory stromal cells.

This finding complements the observations in the macaque model, providing evidence that BMP2 expression in stromal cells is dysregulated in intestinal inflammation across species and age ranges.

(C) UMAP colored by BMP2 expression level (scale: 0-2), revealing hotspots of BMP2 expression (red) predominantly in regions occupied by Inflammatory stromal cells and in areas with higher proportions of UC-derived cells.

BMP2 Co-expression Networks

Correlation analysis revealed strong positive associations between BMP2 and several components of key signaling pathways:

  • TGF- pathway: Positive correlations with TGFB1, SMAD3, and SMAD7
  • WNT pathway: Strong positive correlation with WNT5A (r=0.33, p<0.001)
  • ECM components: Positive correlations with multiple collagen genes
  • Growth factors: Correlations with PDGFC and VEGFA
  • Inflammatory mediators: Correlation with TGFB1 and IL6

These correlation patterns suggest coordinated regulation of BMP2 with genes involved in tissue remodeling and inflammatory responses (Figure 5).

Figure 3. Expression of BMP2 receptors across stromal subtypes in the Kinchen IBD dataset. Violin plots show the distribution of expression values for BMP2 receptors (BMPR1A, BMPR1B, BMPR2, ACVR1, ACVR2A, and ACVR2B) across five stromal subtypes: general stromal cells, inflammatory stromal cells, myofibroblasts, WNT-high stromal cells, and mesothelial cells. Expression values are log-normalized counts from single-cell RNA sequencing data. Note the heterogeneous expression patterns, with inflammatory stromal cells and myofibroblasts showing generally higher expression of most receptors, particularly BMPR2 and ACVR1, suggesting enhanced responsiveness to BMP2 signaling in these subtypes. BMPR1B shows low expression across all subtypes, indicating it may play a minimal role in BMP2 signaling in intestinal stromal populations.

BMP2-Receptor Interaction Analysis

Analysis of BMP2 receptors (BMPR1A, BMPR1B, BMPR2, ACVR1, ACVR2A, ACVR2B) across stromal subtypes revealed complex signaling networks. Interaction potential scores calculated between BMP2-expressing and receptor-expressing stromal subtypes showed particularly strong potential interactions between inflammatory stromal cells and mesothelial cells (Figure 4).

Mesothelial cells displayed high interaction scores with BMP2 from various sources, suggesting they may be major targets of BMP2 signaling in intestinal stroma. Inflammatory stromal cells and myofibroblasts also demonstrated significant interaction potential, particularly through the BMPR2 and ACVR2A receptors.

Figure 4. Heatmap of BMP2-receptor interaction scores across stromal subtypes. Interaction scores were calculated based on the product of average BMP2 expression and receptor expression for each stromal subtype. These scores provide an estimate of potential signaling strength between BMP2-producing cells and receptor-expressing cells. The heatmap reveals strongest interaction potential in inflammatory stromal cells and myofibroblasts, particularly through the BMPR2 and ACVR1 receptors. This pattern suggests these subtypes may be particularly responsive to BMP2 signaling in the inflamed intestinal microenvironment. The interaction scores highlight differential receptor utilization across subtypes, with BMPR1A showing stronger interactions in WNT-high stromal cells compared to other receptors, while BMPR2 dominates the interaction profile in inflammatory stromal cells.

Figure 5. BMP2 correlations with key signaling pathways in human intestinal stromal cells. Bar plots showing Spearman correlation coefficients between BMP2 and genes from key signaling pathways in intestinal stromal cells from healthy controls and ulcerative colitis patients. (A) TGF- pathway genes, (B) WNT pathway genes, (C) Hedgehog pathway genes, (D) Notch pathway genes, (E) BMP pathway genes, (F) ECM pathway genes, (G) Growth factor genes, and (H) Inflammatory pathway genes. Red bars indicate positive correlations while blue bars show negative correlations. The analysis reveals coordinated regulation between BMP2 and multiple components of tissue remodeling and inflammatory pathways.

Cross-Species Implications and Significance

The convergence of evidence from two different speciesnon-human primate and humanand across different developmental stages suggests evolutionary conservation of BMP2 signaling in intestinal stromal cells. The data indicate that:

  • BMP2 expression in stromal cells is elevated in inflammatory conditions across species
  • This dysregulation appears to affect specific stromal subpopulations
  • Complex BMP2 signaling networks operate within the intestinal stroma
  • Microbial disruption (such as antibiotic exposure) may influence stromal BMP2 expression

These findings support the potential clinical relevance of the stromal BMP2 signaling axis in IBD pathogenesis and suggest BMP2 as a candidate therapeutic target in intestinal inflammatory conditions, particularly those associated with early-life dysbiosis.

Methods

Macaque Spatial Transcriptomics

Colon tissue samples were collected from juvenile rhesus macaques with appropriate institutional approval. Spatial transcriptomics analysis using the CosMx platform allowed for visualization and quantification of gene expression in tissue context. Stromal cells were identified using a multi-marker approach (VIM+, PDGFRA/NCAM1+, PTPRC-/PECAM1-/EPCAM-). BMP2 expression was quantified using normalized expression values, and differences between groups were assessed using the Wilcoxon rank-sum test.

Human Single-Cell RNA-seq Analysis

Analysis utilized the Kinchen et al. dataset (Cell, 2018;175(2):372-386.e17) of colonic mesenchymal cells from healthy controls and ulcerative colitis patients. Stromal cell subtypes were classified using established marker genes for general stromal cells, inflammatory stromal cells, myofibroblasts, WNT-high stromal cells, and mesothelial cells. BMP2 and receptor expression were quantified from normalized gene expression data.

Computational Methods

UMAP dimensionality reduction was performed for visualization of cell populations. BMP2 and receptor expression were examined across stromal subtypes and conditions, with significance assessed using appropriate statistical tests. Correlations between BMP2 and genes in key signaling pathways were calculated using Spearman correlation. Interaction scores were calculated as the product of BMP2 and receptor expression to estimate potential signaling strength between different cell populations. All visualizations were created using the ggplot2 package in R.

References
